{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu) 10.4, the text explicitly defines the \"twice-born\" (*dvija*) varṇas as the three upper castes: the Brāhmaṇa, the Kṣatriya, and the Vaiśya.**[^1]\n\nThe verse states: \"The Brahmana, the Kshatriya, and the Vaishya are the three twice-born *varnas*; but the fourth, the Shudra, is of a single birth (*ekajātis tu*); there is no fifth.\"\n\nThis distinction reflects the traditional Hindu view that the first three varṇas undergo the \"second birth\" via the sacred thread ceremony (*upanayana*), initiating them into Vedic study, while the Śūdra does not.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-92e12d).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 10, [full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/).",
